The [base `ReadToEnd` implementation](https://referencesource.microsoft.com/#mscorlib/system/io/textreader.cs,144) does some allocations that can be completely avoided if we provide a specialized implementation.

I found this in #61314, but this PR does *not* claim to address the root cause of that issue. @CyrusNajmabadi @sharwell 

Here's a benchmark showing the reduced allocations (and time) in the new implementation on a 20 kB text.
```
|     Method |                  Job |              Runtime |     Mean |     Error |    StdDev |   Gen 0 |  Gen 1 | Allocated |
|----------- |--------------------- |--------------------- |---------:|----------:|----------:|--------:|-------:|----------:|
|  ReadToEnd |             .NET 6.0 |             .NET 6.0 | 4.433 us | 0.0411 us | 0.0384 us | 14.6332 | 0.0076 |     60 KB |
| ReadToEnd2 |             .NET 6.0 |             .NET 6.0 | 1.359 us | 0.0134 us | 0.0125 us |  4.8771 | 0.0019 |     20 KB |
|  ReadToEnd |        .NET Core 3.1 |        .NET Core 3.1 | 4.993 us | 0.0993 us | 0.1740 us | 14.6484 | 1.8311 |     60 KB |
| ReadToEnd2 |        .NET Core 3.1 |        .NET Core 3.1 | 1.383 us | 0.0100 us | 0.0089 us |  4.8771 | 0.0019 |     20 KB |
|  ReadToEnd | .NET Framework 4.7.2 | .NET Framework 4.7.2 | 4.577 us | 0.0720 us | 0.0674 us | 14.6484 |      - |     60 KB |
| ReadToEnd2 | .NET Framework 4.7.2 | .NET Framework 4.7.2 | 1.333 us | 0.0157 us | 0.0147 us |  4.8771 |      - |     20 KB |
```

<details>
<summary>Source code of the benchmark</summary>

```c#
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;
using System.Text;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Attributes;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Jobs;
using BenchmarkDotNet.Running;
using Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.Host;

BenchmarkRunner.Run<ReadToEndBenchmark>();

[MemoryDiagnoser]
[SimpleJob(RuntimeMoniker.Net472)]
[SimpleJob(RuntimeMoniker.NetCoreApp31)]
[SimpleJob(RuntimeMoniker.Net60)]
public unsafe class ReadToEndBenchmark
{
    private readonly IntPtr _pointer;
    private readonly TemporaryStorageServiceFactory.DirectMemoryAccessStreamReader _reader1;
    private readonly TemporaryStorageServiceFactory.DirectMemoryAccessStreamReader2 _reader2;

    public ReadToEndBenchmark()
    {
        var length = 10 * 1024;
        _pointer = Marshal.AllocHGlobal(length * sizeof(char));

        _reader1 = new((char*)_pointer, length);
        _reader2 = new((char*)_pointer, length);
    }

    [GlobalCleanup]
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        Marshal.FreeHGlobal(_pointer);
    }

    [Benchmark]
    public string ReadToEnd()
    {
        _reader1.Reset();
        return _reader1.ReadToEnd();
    }

    [Benchmark]
    public string ReadToEnd2()
    {
        _reader2.Reset();
        return _reader2.ReadToEnd();
    }
}
```

Note: for the purpose of this benchmark, I copied the `DirectMemoryAccessStreamReader` class and only implemented the method in the new class to be able to compare them in a single benchmark. I also added a `Reset` method to both so that I could test repeated reads without also measuring the allocations for creating the reader:
```diff
        internal sealed unsafe class DirectMemoryAccessStreamReader : TextReaderWithLength
        {
+           private readonly char* _start;
            private char* _position;
            private readonly char* _end;

            public DirectMemoryAccessStreamReader(char* src, int length)
                : base(length)
            {
                RoslynDebug.Assert(src != null);
                RoslynDebug.Assert(length >= 0);

+                _start = src;
                _position = src;
                _end = _position + length;
            }
+
+           public void Reset()
+           {
+               _position = _start;
+           }
```

</details>

