Visual Studio is telling me that a variable assignment is unnecessary, and applying the suggested fix results in a compilation error. This C# code reproduces the issue:
```cs
    abstract class Foo
    {
        protected abstract void bar(out int v1, int v2);

        public Foo()
        {
            int a = 2;
            bar(out a, a);
        }
    }
```

The suggested change is to remove ` = 2`. This results in a compilation error, because the variable `a` is not assigned prior to its use in the call to `bar`.
Interestingly, if I mouse hover over the suggested fix to see a preview, there is a red squiggly line under the second a in the call to `bar` in the preview. The error is already seen by VS before the fix is applied to my code.

Certainly the code could be cleaned up a bit, e.g. by consolidating those two lines as `bar(out int a, 2);`, and such a suggestion would be welcome. But suggesting a change that won't even compile isn't nice.

A bit of a further complication in the code where I actually saw this: using `bar(out int a, 2);` doesn't always work. Here's an example:
```cs
    abstract class Foo
    {
        protected abstract void bar(out int v1, int v2);

        public Foo()
        {
            int a = 2;
        label1:
            bar(out a, a);
            if (a > 0) goto label1;   
        }
    }
```
Obviously the use of goto is bad, and I've already re-structured the code in a way that avoids this issue, so this isn't an important issue at all in my case. But I thought I'd report this bug anyway.

